<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-69
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In 2007, we realized pretax gains of $28&#160;million
    (after-tax, $19&#160;million, or $.04 per diluted share)
    primarily as a result of securities sold or redeemed in the
    normal course of business. In 2006, we realized pretax gains of
    $79&#160;million (after-tax, $51&#160;million, or $.10 per
    diluted share) primarily as a result of bond swaps and the
    liquidation of equity securities held by Aflac U.S.&#160;In
    2005, we realized pretax gains of $262&#160;million (after-tax,
    $167&#160;million, or $.33 per diluted share) primarily as a
    result of bond swaps. We began a bond-swap program in the second
    half of 2005 and concluded it in the first half of 2006. These
    bond swaps took advantage of tax loss carryforwards and also
    resulted in an improvement in overall portfolio credit quality
    and investment income. Impairment charges recognized in 2007
    were $23&#160;million, before taxes. Impairment charges in 2006
    and 2005 were immaterial.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Fair values of debt securities and privately issued equity
    securities were determined using quotations provided by outside
    securities pricing sources
    <FONT style="white-space: nowrap">and/or</FONT>
    compiled using data provided by external debt and equity market
    sources. The data used in estimating fair value include credit
    spreads of comparably credit-rated securities and market
    quotations of securities with similar maturity and call
    structure characteristics. Fair values are then computed using
    standard industry models that provide pricing data based on a
    wide variety of inputs as noted above. The fair values provided
    by outside sources are reviewed internally for reasonableness.
    If a fair value appears unreasonable, the inputs are re-examined
    and the value is confirmed or revised. The fair values for
    publicly traded equity securities were determined using market
    quotations from the public exchange markets where the securities
    are principally traded.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-70
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The following table shows the gross unrealized losses and fair
    values of our investments with unrealized losses that are not
    deemed to be other-than-temporarily impaired, aggregated by
    investment category and length of time that individual
    securities have been in a continuous unrealized loss position at
    December&#160;31, 2007.
</DIV>

</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-71
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The unrealized losses on our investments in government and
    guaranteed fixed-maturity securities, which include
    U.S.&#160;Treasury obligations, direct obligations of
    U.S.&#160;government agencies, Japan government bonds, and
    direct obligations of Japan government agencies were caused by
    changes in interest rates
    <FONT style="white-space: nowrap">and/or</FONT>
    exchange rates. The contractual cash flows of these investments
    are guaranteed by either the U.S.&#160;or Japanese government.
    Furthermore, the contractual terms of these investments do not
    permit the issuer to settle the securities at a price less than
    the amortized cost of the investment. Because we have the
    ability and intent to hold these investments until a recovery of
    fair value, which may be maturity, we do not consider these
    investments to be other-than-temporarily impaired at
    December&#160;31, 2007.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The unrealized losses on the other investment categories in the
    preceding table were caused by changes in interest rates,
    yen/dollar exchange rates,
    <FONT style="white-space: nowrap">and/or</FONT>
    increased credit spreads. For credit-related declines in market
    value, we begin a more focused review of the related
    issuer&#146;s credit ratings, financial statements and other
    available financial data, timeliness of payment, competitive
    environment and any other significant data related to the
    issuer. From those reviews, we evaluate the issuer&#146;s
    continued ability to service our investment. If, based on our
    reviews, we determine that the issuer has the ability to
    continue to service our investment, we conclude that the
    investment is temporarily impaired. Because we have the ability
    and intent to hold these investments until a recovery of fair
    value, which may be maturity, we do not consider these
    investments to be other-than-temporarily impaired at
    December&#160;31, 2007.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Included in the unrealized losses on other corporate
    fixed-maturity securities is an unrealized loss of
    $33&#160;million on Aflac Japan&#146;s $123&#160;million
    (14&#160;billion yen) investment in BAWAG Capital Finance Jersey
    II. The decline in fair value of the security was primarily
    caused by losses BAWAG incurred from lending to the failed
    U.S.&#160;brokerage house REFCO and from derivative speculation
    in 2000. While BAWAG&#146;s credit rating has declined from Baa3
    to Ba1 (Moody&#146;s), we currently believe it is probable we
    will collect all amounts due according to the contractual terms
    of the investment. Therefore, it is expected that our investment
    would not be settled at a price less than the amortized cost of
    the investment. Also included in the unrealized losses on other
    corporate fixed-maturity securities is an unrealized loss of
    $67&#160;million on Aflac Japan&#146;s investment of
    $210&#160;million (24&#160;billion yen) in Tollo Shipping
    Company S.A. Our investment is guaranteed by the issuer&#146;s
    parent, Compa&#241;ia Sudamericana de Vapores S.A. (CSAV). The
    decline in fair value of the security was primarily caused by
    two factors: depressed revenue due to competitive pricing
    pressures in the container shipping industry and weaker
    operating margins due to sharply increased fuel costs. The
    contractual terms of this investment do not permit the issuer or
    its parent to settle the security at a price less than the
    amortized cost of the investment, and give priority to repayment
    of our investment under certain circumstances. While CSAV&#146;s
    credit rating has remained at BB+ (S&#038;P), we currently
    believe it is probable that we will collect all amounts due
    according to the contractual terms of the investment. Therefore,
    it is expected that our investment would not be settled at a
    price less than the amortized cost of the investment. Because we
    have the intent and ability to hold these investments until
    recovery of fair value, which may be the investments&#146;
    respective maturities, we do not consider them to be
    other-than-temporarily impaired at December&#160;31, 2007.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-72
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

</A>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The following table shows the gross unrealized losses and fair
    values of our investments with unrealized losses that are not
    deemed to be other-than-temporarily impaired, aggregated by

    December&#160;31, 2006.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Unrealized gains on available-for-sale securities decreased
    primarily as a result of a higher interest rate environment
    driven by wider credit spreads globally and also as a result of
    foreign currency effects.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

    of our liabilities. The following table presents the approximate
    duration of our yen-denominated assets and liabilities, along
    with premiums, as of December 31.

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Currently, when our debt securities mature, the proceeds may be
    reinvested at a yield below that of the interest required for
    the accretion of policy benefit liabilities on policies issued
    in earlier years. However, our strategy of developing and
    marketing riders to our older policies has helped offset the
    negative investment spread. In spite of the negative investment
    spreads, overall profit margins in Aflac Japan&#146;s aggregate
    block of business are adequate because of profits that continue
    to emerge from changes in mix of business and favorable
    mortality, morbidity and expenses.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-74
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The Parent Company has a portfolio of investment-grade
    available-for-sale fixed-maturity securities totaling
    $109&#160;million at amortized cost and $105&#160;million at
    fair value, which is not included in the table above.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Expected maturities may differ from contractual maturities
    because some issuers have the right to call or prepay
    obligations with or without call or prepayment penalties.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-75
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We own subordinated perpetual debenture securities. These
    securities are subordinated to other debt obligations of the
    issuer, but rank higher than equity securities. Although these
    securities have no contractual maturity, the interest coupons
    that were fixed at issuance subsequently change to a floating
    short-term interest rate of 125 to more than 300&#160;basis
    points above an appropriate market index, generally by the
    25th&#160;year after issuance, thereby creating an economic
    maturity date. The economic maturities of our investments in
    perpetual debentures at December&#160;31, 2007, were as follows:
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<TABLE border="0" width="100%" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    As part of our investment activities, we own investments in
    qualified special purpose entities (QSPEs). At December&#160;31,
    2007, available-for-sale QSPEs totaled $3.2&#160;billion at fair
    value ($3.3&#160;billion at amortized cost, or 6.0% of total
    debt securities), compared with $2.3&#160;billion at fair value
    ($2.3&#160;billion at amortized cost, or 4.7% of total debt
    securities) at December&#160;31, 2006. We have no equity
    interests in any of the QSPEs, nor do we have control over these
    entities. Therefore, our loss exposure is limited to the cost of
    our investment.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We also own investments in variable interest entities (VIEs)
    totaling $2.1&#160;billion at fair value ($2.4&#160;billion at
    amortized cost, or 4.5% of total debt securities) at
    December&#160;31, 2007. We are the primary beneficiary of VIEs
    totaling $1.3&#160;billion at fair value ($1.6&#160;billion at
    amortized cost) and have consolidated our interests in these
    VIEs in accordance with FASB Interpretation No.&#160;46 (revised
    December 2003), Consolidation of Variable Interest Entities. The
    activities of the VIEs that we consolidate are limited to
    holding debt securities and utilizing the cash flows from the
    debt securities to service our investments therein. The terms of
    these debt securities mirror the terms of the notes held by
    Aflac.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We have interests in VIEs in which we are not the primary
    beneficiary and therefore are not required to consolidate
    totaling $760&#160;million at fair value ($853&#160;million at
    amortized cost) as of December&#160;31, 2007. These interests
    primarily consist of corporate collateralized debt obligations
    (CDOs). The activities of these VIEs are limited to holding
    underlying collateral, comprising investment-grade debt
    securities at the time of issuance, and credit default swap
    (CDS) contracts on specific corporate entities and utilizing the
    cash flows from the collateral and CDS contracts to service<BR>

</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-76
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    our investments therein. All corporate entities covered by the
    CDS contracts were investment grade at the time of issuance. Our
    remaining VIEs that we are not required to consolidate consist
    of loans to financing vehicles that are irrevocably and
    unconditionally guaranteed by their corporate parents. These
    VIEs are used to raise financing for their respective parent
    companies in the international capital markets. The guarantors
    of these VIEs were investment grade at the time of issuance.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The loss on any of our VIE investments would be limited to its
    cost.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We lend fixed-maturity securities to financial institutions in
    short-term security lending transactions. These short-term
    security lending arrangements increase investment income with
    minimal risk. Our security lending policy requires that the fair
    value of the securities
    <FONT style="white-space: nowrap">and/or</FONT> cash
    received as collateral be 102% or more of the fair value of the
    loaned securities. At December&#160;31, 2007, we had security
    loans outstanding with a fair value of $790&#160;million, and we
    held cash in the amount of $808&#160;million as collateral for
    these loaned securities. At December&#160;31, 2006, we had
    security loans outstanding with a fair value of
    $780&#160;million, and we held cash in the amount of
    $807&#160;million as collateral for these loaned securities.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    During 2007, we reclassified an investment from held to maturity
    to available for sale as a result of a deterioration in the
    issuer&#146;s creditworthiness. At the date of transfer, this
    debt security had an amortized cost of $169&#160;million. The
    investment was subsequently sold at a realized gain of
    $12&#160;million.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    During 2006, we reclassified an investment from held to maturity
    to available for sale as a result of the issuer&#146;s credit
    rating downgrade. At the date of transfer, this debt security
    had an amortized cost of $118&#160;million and an unrealized
    loss of $15&#160;million.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    During 2005, we reclassified an investment from held to maturity
    to available for sale as a result of the issuer&#146;s credit
    rating downgrade. This debt security had an amortized cost of
    $254&#160;million and an unrealized loss of $46&#160;million at
    the date of transfer.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-77
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The methods of determining the fair values of our investments in
    debt and equity securities are described in Note&#160;3. The
    fair values of notes payable with fixed interest rates were
    obtained from an independent financial information service. The
    fair values of our cross-currency swaps are the expected amounts
    that we would receive or pay to terminate the swaps, taking into
    account current interest rates, foreign currency rates and the
    current creditworthiness of the swap counterparties. The fair
    value of the obligation to the Japanese policyholder protection
    corporation is our estimated share of the industry&#146;s
    obligation calculated on a pro rata basis by projecting our
    percentage of the industry&#146;s premiums and reserves and
    applying that percentage to the total industry obligation
    payable in future years.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The carrying amounts for cash and cash equivalents, receivables,
    accrued investment income, accounts payable, cash collateral and
    payables for security transactions approximated their fair
    values due to the short-term nature of these instruments.
    Consequently, such instruments are not included in the above
    table. The preceding table also excludes liabilities for future
    policy benefits and unpaid policy claims as these liabilities
    are not financial instruments as defined by GAAP.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We have outstanding cross-currency swap agreements related to
    the $450&#160;million senior notes (see Note&#160;7). We have
    designated the foreign currency component of these
    cross-currency swaps as a hedge of the foreign currency exposure
    of our investment in Aflac Japan. The notional amounts and terms
    of the swaps match the principal amount and terms of the senior
    notes.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We entered into cross-currency swaps to minimize the impact of
    foreign currency translation on shareholders&#146; equity and to
    reduce interest expense by converting the dollar-denominated
    principal and interest on the senior notes we issued into
    yen-denominated obligations. By entering into these
    cross-currency swaps, we have been able to reduce our interest
    rate from 6.5% in dollars to 1.67% in yen. See Note&#160;1 for
    information on the accounting policy for cross-currency swaps.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-78
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The components of the fair value of the cross-currency and
    interest rate swaps were reflected as an asset or (liability) in
    the balance sheet as of December 31 as follows:
</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We have entered into interest rate swap agreements related to
    the 20&#160;billion yen variable interest rate Uridashi notes
    (see Note&#160;7). By entering into these contracts, we have
    been able to lock in the interest rate at 1.52% in yen. We have
    designated these interest rate swaps as a hedge of the
    variability in our interest cash flows associated with the
    variable interest rate Uridashi notes. The notional amounts and
    terms of the swaps match the principal amount and terms of the
    variable interest rate Uridashi notes. The swaps had no value at
    inception. Changes in the fair value of the swap contracts are
    recorded in other comprehensive income. The fair value of these
    swaps and related changes in fair value were immaterial during
    the years ended December&#160;31, 2007 and 2006.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We are exposed to credit risk in the event of nonperformance by
    counterparties to our cross-currency and interest rate swaps.
    The counterparties to our swap agreements are U.S.&#160;and
    Japanese financial institutions with the following credit
    ratings as of December&#160;31.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 14pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

<TR>
    <TD width="3%"></TD>
    <TD width="97%"></TD>
</TR>

<TR valign="top">
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">5.&#160;</FONT></B>
</TD>
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">DEFERRED POLICY
    ACQUISITION COSTS AND INSURANCE EXPENSES</FONT></B>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <B>Deferred Policy Acquisition Costs and Insurance Expenses:
    </B>Consolidated policy acquisition costs deferred were
    $1.09&#160;billion in 2007, compared with $1.05&#160;billion in
    2006 and $1.00&#160;billion in 2005. The following table
    presents a rollforward of deferred policy acquisition costs by
    segment for the years ended December&#160;31.
</DIV>

    deferred were 74% in 2007 and 76% in both 2006 and 2005.

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

    insurance expenses were 44% in both 2007 and 2006 and 41% in
    2005. Advertising expense is reported as incurred in insurance
    expenses in the consolidated statements of earnings and was as

    previously capitalized systems development costs for Aflac

<TR valign="top">
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">6.&#160;</FONT></B>
</TD>
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">POLICY
    LIABILITIES</FONT></B>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Our policy liabilities primarily include future policy benefits
    and unpaid policy claims, which accounted for 90% and 5% of
    total policy liabilities at December&#160;31, 2007,
    respectively. We regularly review the adequacy of our policy
    liabilities in total and by component. The liability for future
    policy benefits as of December 31 consisted of the following:
</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The weighted-average interest rates reflected in the
    consolidated statements of earnings for future policy benefits
    for Japanese policies were 4.6% in 2007, 4.7% in 2006 and 4.8%
    in 2005; and for U.S.&#160;policies, 6.2% in 2007, 6.3% in 2006
    and 6.4% in 2005.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-81
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In February 2006, the Parent Company filed a Shelf Registration
    Statement (SRS) with Japanese regulatory authorities to issue up
    to 100&#160;billion yen of yen-denominated Samurai notes in
    Japan. In June 2007, the Parent Company issued yen-denominated
    Samurai notes totaling 30&#160;billion yen. We used the net
    proceeds of these Samurai notes to pay in full the .96% Samurai
    notes that were issued in 2002 and matured in June 2007. These
    Samurai notes issued by the Parent Company in 2007 and those
    issued in 2005 each have five year maturities. Each series of
    Samurai notes pays interest semiannually, may only be redeemed
    prior to maturity upon the occurrence of a tax event as
    specified in the respective bond agreement and is not available
    to U.S.&#160;persons.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-82
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In August 2006, the Parent Company filed an SRS with Japanese
    regulatory authorities to issue up to 100&#160;billion yen of
    yen-denominated Uridashi notes in Japan. In September 2006, the
    Parent Company issued three tranches of Uridashi notes totaling
    45&#160;billion yen. The first tranche totaled 15&#160;billion
    yen and has a five-year maturity. The second tranche totaled
    10&#160;billion yen and has a
    <FONT style="white-space: nowrap">10-year</FONT>
    maturity. The third tranche totaled 20&#160;billion yen and has
    a five-year maturity and a variable interest coupon of six-month
    yen LIBOR plus a spread. We have entered into interest rate
    swaps related to the 20&#160;billion yen variable interest rate
    notes (see Note&#160;4). Each tranche of Uridashi notes pays
    interest semiannually, may only be redeemed prior to maturity
    upon the occurrence of a tax event as specified in the
    respective bond agreement and is not available to
    U.S.&#160;persons. If issued, the 55&#160;billion yen of
    Uridashi notes remaining under the August 2006 SRS will not be
    available to U.S.&#160;persons.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    For our yen-denominated loans, the principal amount as stated in
    dollar terms will fluctuate from period to period due to changes
    in the yen/dollar exchange rate. We have designated all of our
    yen-denominated notes payable as a hedge of the foreign currency
    exposure of our investment in Aflac Japan. We have also
    designated the interest rate swaps on our variable interest rate
    Uridashi notes as a hedge of the variability in our interest
    cash flows associated with these notes.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In 1999, we issued $450&#160;million of senior notes. These
    notes pay interest semiannually and are redeemable at our option
    at any time with a redemption price equal to the principal
    amount of the notes redeemed plus a make-whole premium. We have
    entered into cross-currency swaps related to these notes (see
    Note&#160;4).
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The aggregate contractual maturities of notes payable during
    each of the years after December&#160;31, 2007, are as follows:
</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We were in compliance with all of the covenants of our notes
    payable at December&#160;31, 2007. No events of default or
    defaults occurred during 2007 and 2006.

    <BR>
    II-83

    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">8.&#160;INCOME
    TAXES</FONT></B>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Total income tax expense for the years ended December&#160;31,
    was allocated as follows:
</DIV>

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Changes in unrealized foreign currency translation gains/losses
    included a deferred income tax benefit of $55&#160;million in
    2007, compared with a deferred income tax expense of
    $11&#160;million in 2006 and $122&#160;million in 2005.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-85
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

    rise to deferred income tax assets and liabilities as of
    December 31 were as follows:

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 3pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    A valuation allowance is provided when it is more likely than
    not that deferred tax assets will not be realized. In prior
    years, we established valuation allowances primarily for
    alternative minimum tax credit and noninsurance loss
    carryforwards that exceeded projected future offsets. Under
    U.S.&#160;income tax rules, only 35% of noninsurance losses can
    be offset against life insurance taxable income each year.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 3pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We received regulatory approval for a change in the allocation
    of expenses under the management fee agreement between Aflac and
    the Parent Company in 2005. This enabled the Parent Company to
    fully utilize its tax-basis, non-life operating losses and
    therefore release the valuation allowance on the associated
    deferred tax assets, resulting in a benefit of $34&#160;million
    ($.07 per diluted share) in 2005. For current U.S.&#160;income
    tax purposes, there were no alternative minimum tax credit
    carryforwards available at December&#160;31, 2007.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 3pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We file federal income tax returns in the United States and
    Japan as well as state or prefecture income tax returns in
    various jurisdictions in the two countries. U.S.&#160;federal
    and state income tax returns for years before 2002 are no longer
    subject to examination. We have been examined through
    March&#160;31, 2004, for Japanese tax purposes.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-86
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We adopted the provisions of FASB Interpretation No.&#160;48,
    Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes (FIN&#160;48), on
    January&#160;1, 2007 (see Note&#160;1). There was no change in
    the liability for unrecognized tax benefits as a result of the
    implementation of FIN&#160;48 and therefore no adjustment to
    retained earnings upon adoption. A reconciliation of the
    beginning and ending amount of unrecognized tax benefits is as
    follows:

    <TD valign="bottom">

    $18 at December&#160;31, 2007.</FONT></I></TD>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Included in the balance of the liability for unrecognized tax
    benefits at December&#160;31, 2007, are $51&#160;million of tax
    positions for which the ultimate deductibility is highly
    certain, but for which there is uncertainty about the timing of
    such deductibility. Because of the impact of deferred tax
    accounting, other than interest and penalties, the disallowance
    of the shorter deductibility period would not affect the annual
    effective tax rate, but would accelerate the payment of cash to
    the taxing authority to an earlier period. The Company has
    accrued approximately $2&#160;million for permanent
    uncertainties, which if reversed would not have a material
    effect on the annual effective rate.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The Company recognizes accrued interest and penalties related to
    unrecognized tax benefits in income tax expense. We recognized
    approximately $3&#160;million in interest and penalties in 2007,
    compared with $2&#160;million in 2006 and $1&#160;million in
    2005. The Company has accrued approximately $32&#160;million for
    the payment of interest and penalties as of December&#160;31,
    2007, compared with $29&#160;million a year ago.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    As of December&#160;31, 2007, there were no material uncertain
    tax positions for which the total amounts of unrecognized tax
    benefits will significantly increase or decrease within the next
    twelve months.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-87
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Outstanding share-based awards are excluded from the calculation
    of weighted-average shares used in the computation of basic
    earnings per share. Stock options to purchase approximately
    1.7&#160;million shares, on a weighted-average basis, as of
    December&#160;31, 2007, were considered to be anti-dilutive and
    were excluded from the calculation of diluted earnings per
    share, compared with 1.8&#160;million shares in 2006 and
    2.5&#160;million in 2005. The weighted-average shares used in
    calculating earnings per share for the years ended December 31
    were as follows:
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <B>Share Repurchase Program:</B>&#160;In 2004, the Board of
    Directors authorized the purchase of 30.0&#160;million shares of
    our common stock. We exhausted that authorization during the
    second quarter of 2007. In 2006, the Board of Directors
    authorized the purchase of 30.0&#160;million shares of our
    common stock. As of December&#160;31, 2007, approximately
    25.6&#160;million shares were available for purchase under the
    2006&#160;share repurchase authorization. In January 2008, the
    Board authorized the purchase of an additional 30.0&#160;million
    shares of our common stock.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <B>Voting Rights:</B>&#160;In accordance with the Parent
    Company&#146;s articles of incorporation, shares of common stock
    are generally entitled to one vote per share until they have
    been held by the same beneficial owner for a continuous period
    of 48&#160;months, at which time they become entitled to 10
    votes per share.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-88
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 14pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

<TR>
    <TD width="4%"></TD>
    <TD width="96%"></TD>
</TR>

<TR valign="top">
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">10.&#160;</FONT></B>
</TD>
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">SHARE-BASED
    TRANSACTIONS</FONT></B>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    As of December&#160;31, 2007, the Company has outstanding
    share-based awards under two long-term incentive compensation
    plans.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The first plan, which expired in February 2007, is a stock
    option plan which allowed grants for incentive stock options
    (ISOs) to employees and non-qualifying stock options (NQSOs) to
    employees and non-employee directors. The options have a term of
    10&#160;years and generally vest after three years. The strike
    price of options granted under this plan is equal to the fair
    market value of a share of the Company&#146;s common stock at
    the date of grant. Options granted before the plan&#146;s
    expiration date remain outstanding in accordance with their
    terms.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The second long-term incentive compensation plan allows awards
    to Company employees for ISOs, NQSOs, restricted stock,
    restricted stock units, and stock appreciation rights.
    Non-employee directors are eligible for grants of NQSOs,
    restricted stock, and stock appreciation rights. Generally, the
    awards vest based upon time-based conditions or time- and
    performance-based conditions. Performance-based vesting
    conditions generally include the attainment of goals related to
    Company financial performance. As of December&#160;31, 2007,
    approximately 22.6&#160;million shares were available for future
    grants under this plan, and the only performance-based awards
    issued and outstanding were restricted stock awards.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Share-based awards granted to
    <FONT style="white-space: nowrap">U.S.-based</FONT>
    grantees are settled upon exercise with authorized but unissued
    Company stock, while those issued to Japan-based grantees are
    settled upon exercise with treasury shares.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The following table presents the expense recognized in
    connection with share-based awards for the periods ended
    December&#160;31.
</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We estimate the fair value of each stock option granted using
    the Black-Scholes-Merton multiple option approach. Expected
    volatility is based on historical periods generally commensurate
    with the estimated term of options. We use historical data to
    estimate option exercise and termination patterns within the
    model. Separate groups of employees that have similar historical
    exercise patterns are stratified and considered separately for
    valuation purposes. The expected term of options granted is
    derived from the output of our option model and represents the
    weighted-average period of time that options granted are
    expected to be outstanding. We base the risk-free interest rate
    on the Treasury note rate with a term comparable to that of the
    estimated term of options. The weighted-average fair value of
    options at their grant date was $16.06 for 2007, compared with
    $15.28 for 2006 and $13.40<BR>

</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-89
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->

</A>

    in 2005. The following table presents the assumptions used in
    valuing options granted during the years ended December&#160;31.
</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    As of December&#160;31, 2007, the aggregate intrinsic value of
    stock options outstanding was $467&#160;million, with a
    weighted-average remaining term of 5.5&#160;years. The aggregate
    intrinsic value of stock options exercisable at that same date
    was $398&#160;million, with a weighted-average remaining term of
    4.6&#160;years. The total intrinsic value of stock options
    exercised during the year ended December&#160;31, 2007, was
    $154&#160;million, compared with $62&#160;million in 2006 and
    $114&#160;million in 2005. We received cash from the exercise of
    stock options in the amount of $52&#160;million in 2007,
    compared with $38&#160;million in 2006 and $49&#160;million in
    2005. The tax benefit realized as a result of stock option
    exercises was $51&#160;million in 2007, $19&#160;million in 2006
    and $37&#160;million in 2005.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 3pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The value of restricted stock awards is based on the fair market
    value of our common stock at the date of grant. The following
    table summarizes restricted stock activity during the years
    ended December&#160;31.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-91
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    As of December&#160;31, 2007, total compensation cost not yet
    recognized in our financial statements related to restricted
    stock awards was $20&#160;million, of which $9&#160;million
    (492&#160;thousand shares) was related to share-based awards
    with a performance-based vesting condition. We expect to
    recognize these amounts over a weighted-average period of
    approximately 1.3&#160;years. There are no other contractual
    terms covering restricted stock awards once vested.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 14pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

<TR>
    <TD width="4%"></TD>
    <TD width="96%"></TD>
</TR>

<TR valign="top">
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">11.&#160;</FONT></B>
</TD>
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">STATUTORY
    ACCOUNTING AND DIVIDEND RESTRICTIONS</FONT></B>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Our insurance subsidiary is required to report its results of
    operations and financial position to state insurance regulatory
    authorities on the basis of statutory accounting practices
    prescribed or permitted by such authorities.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    As determined on a U.S.&#160;statutory accounting basis,
    Aflac&#146;s net income was $1.8&#160;billion in 2007,
    $1.7&#160;billion in 2006 and $1.3&#160;billion in 2005. Capital
    and surplus was $4.2 billion at both December&#160;31, 2007 and
    2006.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Net assets of the insurance subsidiaries aggregated
    $9.1&#160;billion at December&#160;31, 2007, on a GAAP basis,
    compared with $9.3&#160;billion a year ago. Aflac Japan
    accounted for $6.0&#160;billion, or 66.8%, of these net assets,
    compared with $5.7&#160;billion, or 62.0%, at December&#160;31,
    2006.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Reconciliations of Aflac&#146;s net assets on a GAAP basis to
    capital and surplus determined on a U.S.&#160;statutory
    accounting basis as of December&#160;31 were as follows:
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Aflac Japan must report its results of operations and financial
    position to the Japanese Financial Services Agency (FSA) on a
    Japanese regulatory accounting basis as prescribed by the FSA.
    Capital and surplus (unaudited) of Aflac Japan, based on
    Japanese regulatory accounting practices, aggregated
    $2.5&#160;billion at December&#160;31, 2007, and
    $2.6&#160;billion at December&#160;31, 2006. Japanese regulatory
    accounting practices differ in many respects from
    U.S.&#160;GAAP. Under Japanese regulatory accounting practices,
    policy acquisition costs are charged off immediately; deferred
    income tax liabilities are recognized on a different basis;
    policy benefit and claim reserving methods and assumptions are
    different; the carrying value of securities transferred to held
    to maturity is different; policyholder protection corporation
    obligations are not accrued; and premium income is recognized on
    a cash basis.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 12pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The Parent Company depends on its subsidiaries for cash flow,
    primarily in the form of dividends and management fees.
    Consolidated retained earnings in the accompanying financial
    statements largely represent the undistributed earnings of our
    insurance subsidiary. Amounts available for dividends,
    management fees and other payments to the Parent Company by its
    insurance subsidiary<BR>

</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-92
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    may fluctuate due to different accounting methods required by
    regulatory authorities. These payments are also subject to
    various regulatory restrictions and approvals related to
    safeguarding the interests of insurance policyholders. Our
    insurance subsidiary must maintain adequate risk-based capital
    for U.S.&#160;regulatory authorities and our Japan branch must
    maintain adequate solvency margins for Japanese regulatory
    authorities. Additionally, the maximum amount of dividends that
    can be paid to the Parent Company by Aflac without prior
    approval of Nebraska&#146;s director of insurance is the greater
    of the net gain from operations, which excludes net realized
    investment gains, for the previous year determined under
    statutory accounting principles, or 10% of statutory capital and
    surplus as of the previous year-end. Dividends declared by Aflac
    during 2008 in excess of $1.7&#160;billion would require such
    approval. Dividends declared by Aflac during 2007 were
    $1.4&#160;billion.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    A portion of Aflac Japan earnings, as determined on a Japanese
    regulatory accounting basis, can be repatriated each year to
    Aflac U.S.&#160;after complying with solvency margin provisions
    and satisfying various conditions imposed by Japanese regulatory
    authorities for protecting policyholders. Profit repatriations
    to the United States can fluctuate due to changes in the amounts
    of Japanese regulatory earnings. Among other items, factors
    affecting regulatory earnings include Japanese regulatory
    accounting practices and fluctuations in currency translation of
    Aflac Japan&#146;s dollar-denominated investments and related
    investment income into yen. Profits repatriated by Aflac Japan
    to Aflac U.S.&#160;were as follows for the years ended
    December&#160;31:
</DIV>

<TR valign="top">
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">12.&#160;</FONT></B>

    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">BENEFIT
    PLANS</FONT></B>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>

<DIV style="margin-top: 3pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Our basic employee defined-benefit pension plans cover
    substantially all of our full-time employees in the United
    States and Japan. At December&#160;31, 2007, other liabilities
    included a liability for both plans in the amount of
    $82&#160;million, compared with $102&#160;million a year ago. We
    plan to make contributions of $20&#160;million to the
    U.S.&#160;plan and $12&#160;million to the Japanese plan in 2008.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    On December&#160;31, 2006, we adopted the recognition and
    disclosure provisions and early adopted the measurement date
    provisions of SFAS&#160;158. SFAS&#160;158 requires the
    recognition of the funded status (i.e., the difference between
    the fair value of plan assets and the projected benefit
    obligations) of our benefit plans in our financial statements,
    with a corresponding adjustment to accumulated other
    comprehensive income, net of tax. The adjustment to accumulated
    other comprehensive income at adoption represents the net
    unrecognized actuarial losses, unrecognized prior service costs
    or credits, as applicable, and the unrecognized transition asset
    remaining from the initial adoption of SFAS&#160;87, all of
    which were previously netted against the plan&#146;s funded
    status in the past under the provisions of SFAS&#160;87. These
    amounts will be subsequently recognized as net periodic pension
    cost over future periods consistent with our historical
    accounting policy for amortizing such amounts. Further, the
    components of the benefit obligations that arise in subsequent
    periods and are not recognized as net periodic pension cost in
    the same periods are recognized as a component of other
    comprehensive income. Those amounts will also be subsequently
    recognized as a component of net periodic pension cost as
    previously described. The adoption of SFAS&#160;158 had no
    effect on our net earnings for any period presented, and it will
    not affect our operating results in future periods.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-93
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    No prior service costs or credits arose during 2007 and the
    amounts of prior service costs and credits as well as transition
    obligation amortized to expense were immaterial for the years
    ended December&#160;31, 2007 and 2006. Amortization of actuarial
    losses to expense in 2008 is estimated to be $1&#160;million for
    the Japanese plan and $2&#160;million for the U.S.&#160;plan,
    while the amortization of prior service costs and credits are
    expected to be negligible.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 0%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Equity securities held by our U.S.&#160;plan included
    $4&#160;million (2.5% of plan assets) of Aflac Incorporated
    common stock at December&#160;31, 2007, compared with
    $3&#160;million (2.2% of plan assets) at December&#160;31, 2006.
    Target asset allocations for U.S.&#160;plan assets are 60% to
    65% equity securities, 35% to 40% fixed-income securities and 0%
    to 3% cash and cash equivalents. Target asset allocations for
    Japanese plan assets are 34% equity securities and 66%
    fixed-income securities. As discussed below, the investment
    strategy of our pension plans is long-term in nature.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-95
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
<!-- PAGEBREAK -->
<P><HR noshade><P>
<H5 align="left" style="page-break-before:always">&nbsp;</H5><P>

<DIV style="width: 94%; margin-left: 3%"><!-- BEGIN PAGE WIDTH -->
<P>
<DIV  align="left" style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: times">
<A href="#998">
Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV><P>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    The investment objective of our U.S.&#160;and Japanese plans is
    to preserve the purchasing power of the plan&#146;s assets and
    earn a reasonable inflation adjusted rate of return over the
    long term. Furthermore, we seek to accomplish these objectives
    in a manner that allows for the adequate funding of plan
    benefits and expenses. In order to achieve these objectives, our
    goal is to maintain a conservative, well-diversified and
    balanced portfolio of high-quality equity, fixed-income and
    money market securities. As a part of our strategy, we have
    established strict policies covering quality, type and
    concentration of investment securities. For our U.S.&#160;plan,
    these policies prohibit investments in precious metals, limited
    partnerships, venture capital, and direct investments in real
    estate. We are also prohibited from trading on margin. For our
    Japanese plan, these policies include limitations on investments
    in derivatives including futures, options and swaps, and
    low-liquidity investments such as real estate, venture capital
    investments, and privately issued securities.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We monitor the U.S.&#160;plan&#146;s performance over a three-
    to five-year period utilizing shorter time frame performance
    measures to identify trends. We review investment performance
    and compliance with stated investment policies and practices on
    a quarterly basis. The specific investment objectives for the
    U.S.&#160;pension plan are: to exceed a composite of asset class
    target returns, weighted according to the plan&#146;s target
    asset allocation; and to outperform the median fund from a
    universe of similarly managed corporate pension funds. Both
    objectives are measured over a rolling three- to five-year
    period. We monitor the Japanese plan&#146;s asset allocation and
    compliance with stated investment policies and practices. The
    Japanese plan&#146;s performance is reviewed on a quarterly
    basis by asset allocation. The specific investment objective for
    the Japanese plan is to outperform the projected long-term rate
    of return used to determine the Japanese plan&#146;s pension
    obligation.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    Expected future benefit payments for the U.S.&#160;and Japanese
    plans are as follows:
</DIV>

<TD align="left" valign="bottom">
<DIV style="text-indent: -11pt; margin-left: 11pt">
    <B>Components of net periodic<BR>
    benefit cost:</B>

<TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

<TR>
    <TD width="1%"></TD>
    <TD width="1%"></TD>
    <TD width="98%"></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
    <TD valign="top">
    <I><FONT style="font-size: 10pt">* </FONT></I></TD>
    <TD></TD>
    <TD valign="bottom">
    <I><FONT style="font-size: 10pt">Not applicable</FONT></I></TD>

</TABLE>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In Japan, participant salary and future salary increases are not
    factors in determining pension benefit cost or the related
    pension benefit obligation.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We base the long-term rate of return on U.S.&#160;plan assets on
    the historical rates of return over the last 15&#160;years and
    the expectation of similar returns over the long-term investment
    goals and objectives of U.S.&#160;plan assets. We base the
    long-term rate of return on the Japanese plan assets on the
    historical rates of return over the last 10&#160;years.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In addition to the benefit obligations for funded employee
    plans, we also maintain unfunded supplemental retirement plans
    for certain officers and beneficiaries. Retirement expense for
    these unfunded supplemental plans was $5&#160;million in 2007,
    $16&#160;million in 2006 and $20&#160;million in 2005. The
    accrued retirement liability for the unfunded supplemental
    retirement plans was $204&#160;million at December&#160;31,
    2007, compared with $209&#160;million a year ago. The
    assumptions used in the valuation of these plans were the same
    as for the funded plans.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <B>Stock Bonus Plan:</B>&#160;Aflac U.S.&#160;maintains a stock
    bonus plan for eligible U.S.&#160;sales associates. Plan
    participants receive shares of Aflac Incorporated common stock
    based on their new annualized premium sales and their first-year
    persistency of substantially all new insurance policies. The
    cost of this plan, which is included in deferred policy
    acquisition costs, amounted to $45&#160;million in 2007,
    $40&#160;million in 2006 and $37&#160;million in 2005.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-97
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->

</A>
</DIV><P>

<TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 14pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">

<TR>
    <TD width="4%"></TD>
    <TD width="96%"></TD>
</TR>

<TR valign="top">
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">13.&#160;</FONT></B>
</TD>
    <TD>
    <B><FONT style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica">COMMITMENTS AND
    CONTINGENT LIABILITIES</FONT></B>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We have three outsourcing agreements with IBM. The first
    agreement provides mainframe computer operations and support for
    Aflac Japan. It has a remaining term of eight years and an
    aggregate remaining cost of 24.4&#160;billion yen
    ($213&#160;million using the December&#160;31, 2007, exchange
    rate). The second agreement provides distributed computer
    operations and support for Aflac Japan. It has a remaining term
    of eight years and an aggregate remaining cost of
    30.4&#160;billion yen ($266&#160;million using the
    December&#160;31, 2007, exchange rate). The third agreement
    provides application maintenance and development services for
    Aflac Japan. It has a remaining term of five years and an
    aggregate remaining cost of 8.8&#160;billion yen
    ($77&#160;million using the December&#160;31, 2007, exchange
    rate).
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We have entered into two additional outsourcing agreements to
    provide application maintenance and development services for our
    Japanese operation. The first agreement with Accenture has a
    remaining term of six years with an aggregate remaining cost of
    4.7&#160;billion yen ($41&#160;million using the
    December&#160;31, 2007, exchange rate). The second agreement
    with NTT DATA has a remaining term of three years with an
    aggregate remaining cost of 1.0&#160;billion yen
    ($9&#160;million using the December&#160;31, 2007, exchange
    rate).
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We lease office space and equipment under agreements that expire
    in various years through 2022. Future minimum lease payments due
    under non-cancelable operating leases at December&#160;31, 2007,
    were as follows:
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 9pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    In 2005, we announced a multiyear building project for
    additional office space in Columbus, Georgia. The initial phase
    was completed in 2007 at a cost of $27&#160;million. The second
    phase of the expansion is to be completed in 2009 and is
    expected to cost approximately $48&#160;million.
</DIV>

<DIV style="margin-top: 6pt; font-size: 1pt">&nbsp;</DIV>

<DIV align="left" style="margin-left: 0%; margin-right: 0%; text-indent: 4%; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    We are a defendant in various lawsuits considered to be in the
    normal course of business. Members of our senior legal and
    financial management teams review litigation on a quarterly and
    annual basis. The final results of any litigation cannot be
    predicted with certainty. Although some of this litigation is
    pending in states where large punitive damages, bearing little
    relation to the actual damages sustained by plaintiffs, have
    been awarded in recent years, we believe the outcome of pending
    litigation will not have a material adverse effect on our
    financial position, results of operations, or cash flows.
</DIV>

<P align="center" style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Arial, Helvetica; color: #000000; background: #FFFFFF">
    <BR>
    II-98
</DIV><!-- END PAGE WIDTH -->
